  "prompt": "What is kidney function test?",
  "response": "A kidney function test is a group of tests used to assess how well the kidneys are working. These tests measure various substances in the blood and urine to evaluate kidney health, detect kidney disease, monitor kidney function over time, and determine the severity of kidney damage. Here are the common types of kidney function tests:\n\n### 1. **Blood Tests:**\n   - **Serum Creatinine:** Creatinine is a waste product produced by muscle metabolism. Healthy kidneys filter it out of the blood. Elevated levels may indicate impaired kidney function.\n   - **Blood Urea Nitrogen (BUN):** Measures the amount of nitrogen in the blood that comes from urea, a waste product of protein metabolism. High levels can suggest kidney dysfunction.\n   - **Glomerular Filtration Rate (GFR):** Estimates how much blood passes through the glomeruli (tiny filters in the kidneys) each minute. A low GFR suggests reduced kidney function.\n\n### 2. **Urine Tests:**\n   - **Urinalysis:** Examines the urine for abnormalities such as protein, blood, or white blood cells, which can indicate kidney problems.\n   - **Albumin-to-Creatinine Ratio (ACR):** Measures the amount of albumin (a protein) in the urine. High levels can be a sign of kidney damage, especially in people with diabetes or hypertension.\n   - **24-Hour Urine Collection:** Measures the total amount of certain substances (e.g., protein, creatinine) excreted in the urine over 24 hours to assess kidney function.\n\n### 3. **Imaging Tests:**\n   - **Ultrasound:** Uses sound waves to create images of the kidneys, helping to detect structural abnormalities or blockages.\n   - **CT Scan or MRI:** Provides detailed images of the kidneys and surrounding structures to identify tumors, cysts, or other issues.\n\n### Why Are Kidney Function Tests Done?\n   - To diagnose kidney disease or dysfunction.\n   - To monitor the progression of chronic kidney disease (CKD).\n   - To evaluate the impact of conditions like diabetes or hypertension on the kidneys.\n   - To assess kidney function before or after starting certain medications.\n\n### When Are They Ordered?\n   - If symptoms of kidney disease are present (e.g., swelling, fatigue, changes in urination).\n   - If you have risk factors for kidney disease (e.g., diabetes, high blood pressure, family history).\n   - As part of routine health check-ups.\n\nIf kidney function tests indicate abnormalities, further evaluation and treatment by a healthcare provider are essential to manage the condition and prevent complications.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
